<section id="intro">

<h2>1.1 Introduction</h2>

<p>

Statistics plays a vital role in modern science, business, agriculture, medicine, and technology. 
Originally statistics was related to state administration but today it is used in almost every 
field to analyze data and support decision making.

</p>

<p>

Statistics is mainly concerned with collecting, organizing, analyzing and interpreting numerical data.

</p>

<div class="highlight">

Examples of statistical data include:

<ul>

<li>Population growth</li>
<li>Crop production</li>
<li>Business profits</li>
<li>Medical research results</li>

</ul>

</div>

</section>

<section id="meaning">

<h2>1.2 Meaning of Statistics</h2>

<p>

The word statistics is used in two senses.

</p>

<h3>Statistics in Singular Sense</h3>

<p>

Statistics refers to a branch of science dealing with methods of collecting, presenting,
analyzing and interpreting data.

</p>

<h3>Statistics in Plural Sense</h3>

<p>

Statistics refers to numerical facts and figures arranged systematically.

</p>

<p>Examples:</p>

<ul>

<li>Population statistics</li>
<li>Economic growth data</li>
<li>Agricultural production statistics</li>

</ul>

</section>

<section id="definitions">

<h2>1.3 Definitions of Statistics</h2>

<table>

<tr>
<th>Statistician</th>
<th>Definition</th>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Croxton and Cowden</td>
<td>Statistics is the science of collecting, presenting, analyzing and interpreting numerical data.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>R.A. Fisher</td>
<td>Statistics is a branch of applied mathematics dealing with observational data.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Lovitt</td>
<td>Statistics deals with classification and tabulation of numerical facts.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>A.L. Bowley</td>
<td>Statistics is the science of counting and measuring social phenomena.</td>
</tr>

</table>

</section>

<section id="types">

<h2>1.4 Types of Statistics</h2>

<h3>Descriptive Statistics</h3>

<p>

Descriptive statistics summarizes and presents data using tables, charts and averages.

</p>

Examples include:

<ul>

<li>Mean</li>
<li>Median</li>
<li>Mode</li>
<li>Charts and graphs</li>

</ul>

<h3>Inferential Statistics</h3>

<p>

Inferential statistics uses sample data to draw conclusions about a population.

</p>

Examples include:

<ul>

<li>Hypothesis testing</li>
<li>Regression analysis</li>
<li>Confidence intervals</li>

</ul>

</section>

<section id="nature">

<h2>1.5 Nature of Statistics</h2>

<p>

Statistics is both a science and an art.

</p>

<h3>Statistics as Science</h3>

<ul>

<li>Uses systematic methods</li>
<li>Follows scientific principles</li>
<li>Analyzes relationships among variables</li>

</ul>

<h3>Statistics as Art</h3>

<ul>

<li>Requires skill in interpretation</li>
<li>Requires experience in data analysis</li>

</ul>

</section>

<section id="aims">

<h2>1.6 Aims of Statistics</h2>

<ul>

<li>To study populations</li>
<li>To understand variation in data</li>
<li>To summarize large amounts of information</li>
<li>To assist in decision making</li>

</ul>

</section>

<section id="functions">

<h2>1.7 Functions of Statistics</h2>

<ul>

<li>Simplifies complex data</li>
<li>Facilitates comparison</li>
<li>Helps in forecasting future trends</li>
<li>Tests scientific hypotheses</li>
<li>Supports policy decisions</li>

</ul>

</section>

<section id="applications">

<h2>1.8 Applications of Statistics</h2>

<h3>Government</h3>

<ul>
<li>Budget preparation</li>
<li>Economic planning</li>
<li>Population studies</li>
</ul>

<h3>Business</h3>

<ul>
<li>Market research</li>
<li>Demand forecasting</li>
<li>Production planning</li>
</ul>

<h3>Medicine</h3>

<ul>
<li>Drug testing</li>
<li>Disease analysis</li>
</ul>

<h3>Agriculture</h3>

<ul>
<li>Crop yield experiments</li>
<li>Soil classification</li>
<li>Fertilizer research</li>
</ul>

</section>

<section id="limitations">

<h2>1.9 Limitations of Statistics</h2>

<ul>

<li>Statistics deals only with numerical data.</li>
<li>It studies aggregates rather than individuals.</li>
<li>Results are approximate and not exact.</li>
<li>Statistics can be misused if interpreted incorrectly.</li>

</ul>

</section>

<section id="summary">

<h2>Chapter Summary</h2>

<p>

Statistics is a powerful tool used for collecting, analyzing and interpreting data.
It has wide applications in government, business, agriculture and science. 
Despite some limitations, statistical methods are essential for research and decision making.

</p>

</section>

</main>

